"{\"uid\": \"si.com-golf-rory-mcilroy-seeking-olympic-redemption-paris-st-andrews\", \"text\": \"SAINT QUENTIN-EN-YVELINES, France \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Video and social media posts surfaced Monday of Rory McIlroy getting in a round of golf ... at the Old Course?  Yep, McIlroy was at the Home of Golf in St. Andrews, Scotland, playing the storied links where he painfully lost the 2022 British Open as Cam Smith blew by him with a final-round 64 to snag the Claret Jug, one of a handful of painful brushes with a major title over the past decade.  Rory McIlroy is preparing for@OlympicGolfin Paris with a round on The Old Course at St Andrews this afternoon.Here he is hitting his tee shot on the 12th hole.pic.twitter.com/7WBbwRYPBR  McIlroy seemed a bit put off by a question about it, fair as it was given that it seemed an odd place to be prior to this week\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Olympic Golf Tournament on a course that is in no way, shape or form like St. Andrews.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cYeah, none of your business why I was there but it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s always nice to play St. Andrews,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d McIlroy said Tuesday during a media gathering along with fellow Irish representative Shane Lowry at Le Golf National, site of this week\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s tournament.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was good. I wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t expecting quite the crowd on the last few holes that we got but yeah, it was good. That was the first game of golf I have had since Troon. I thought at least one game of golf before I got here was probably beneficial.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  MORE:Tee times for the first two rounds at Le Golf National  McIlroy was referencing theOpen won by Xander Schauffeletwo weeks ago at Royal Troon,where he missed the cutand played poorly in doing so. That came after a tie for fourth at the Scottish Open, which followed atough-luck loss to Bryson DeChambeauat the U.S. Open.  The Olympics offers an opportunity to earn a prize he once believed was not worth pursuing. In 2016, McIlroy skipped the Games despite being eligible.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI'd say my focus is pretty high,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d said McIlroy, 35, who is ranked third in the Official World Golf Ranking. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe last time you guys saw me, I did not give a very good account of myself at Troon. I want to make sure I am right where I need to be teeing off on Thursday.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAgain, I have been asked this question a lot, where would an Olympic medal sit in sort of the hierarchy of my career achievements and it's something I probably will not be able to answer until when everything is said and done.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI think as golf is in the Olympics for a longer period of time, it will become ... I do not know if anything will be able to sit alongside the majors. We have our four events a year that are the gold standard. But I think this is going to be, in time, right up there amongst that.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  And as it relates to him specifically, McIlroy said: \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt would be the achievement, certainly of the year ... for me, it's well documented that I have not won one of the big four in 10 years. It would probably be one if, if not the biggest in my career for the last 10 years.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Lowry has his own disappointment to overcome. He was the 36-hole leader at Royal Troon and struggled in the worst of the conditions on Saturday, shooting 6-over-par 77 and eventually finishing sixth.  The winner of the 2019 Open at Royal Portrush, Lowry\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094who won the Zurich Classic of New Orleans earlier this year with McIlroy as his partner\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094sees a chance to atone.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI felt I had a good chance to win the Open a couple weeks ago and I was really disappointed to not give it a better go on Saturday and Sunday,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cStraightaway after that, I sort of felt like I have a chance to redeem myself here in a couple of weeks.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cFor me, look, if you look at the media and what it was like back home yesterday when Mona (McSharry) won that bronze medal, I think if I was to win a gold medal and bring it back to Ireland, yeah, it would be pretty cool.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Lowry has already had a life-altering experience at the Olympics, taking part in the opening ceremony in which he was the Irish flag bearer.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was amazing,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Lowry said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was an amazing experience and something that I will remember forever. It was a big honor and when I got there and got to experience the whole thing ... memories for a lifetime and just even being there and being around the other athletes, it was pretty cool.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTo see the Olympics from there, it's something that when I was growing up, you never\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094as a golfer, you did not really think was going to be achievable. So yeah, it was an amazing experience.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  McIlroy finished tied for third at the 2021 Olympics in Japan and lost in a seven-way playoff for the bronze medal. Lowry was tied for 22nd in Tokyo.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Bob Harig is a senior writer covering golf for Sports Illustrated. He has more than 25 years experience on the beat, including 15 at ESPN. Harig is a regular guest on Sirius XM PGA Tour Radio and has written two books, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cDRIVE: The Lasting Legacy of Tiger Woods\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTiger and Phil: Golf\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Most Fascinating Rivalry.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d He graduated from Indiana University where he earned an Evans Scholarship, named in honor of the great amateur golfer Charles (Chick) Evans Jr. Harig, a former president of the Golf Writers Association of America, lives in Clearwater, Fla.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED